5-RUN COMPARISON
----------------
Same input: /tmp/whisper-swap/utter_16k.wav (2.32 s of espeak'd
"walk forward now please stop", 16 kHz mono)

A) TFLite-enc + pytorch-dec, laptop, COLD subprocess (current daemon path):
   outer wall (subprocess.run to the runner, matching how robot_daemon.py
   calls it today):  5.01, 5.11, 5.00, 5.11, 5.57   mean 5.16 s
   Transcript: "Walk forward now, please stop."  (identical across all 5)
   Dominated by Python import + torch/tf/whisper load per call (~2.2 s)
   plus pytorch model weights load (~0.7 s).

B) TFLite-enc + pytorch-dec, laptop, WARM (persistent Python process,
   module imported once, caches reused):
   wall:  0.99, 1.00, 1.50, 1.55, 1.23   mean 1.25 s
   Breakdown per run:
     mel ~15-25 ms, encoder 611-1061 ms, decoder 280-420 ms.
   Transcript: "Walk forward now, please stop."  (identical across all 5)

C) whisper.cpp, Pixel 6 via adb, ggml-tiny.bin, 8 threads (baseline):
   CMD: adb shell "cd /data/local/tmp && ./whisper-cli -m ggml-tiny.bin
                   -f utter_16k.wav --no-timestamps -l en -t 8"
   wall: 1.75, 1.80, 1.65, 1.98, 1.82   mean 1.80 s
   Transcript: "Walk forward now, please."  (all 5, drops "stop" — a
   tiny model decoding artifact, not an infrastructure issue)

test.wav (RMS 0.0018):
  whisper.cpp on phone: [BLANK_AUDIO] (too quiet)
  TFLite-enc+pytorch-dec laptop: "you"  (filler, same semantic outcome)
  Not a useful accuracy comparison; reported here for completeness.

HEADLINE
--------
Warm in-process: TFLite-enc laptop beats whisper.cpp phone by 1.44x
                 (1.25 s vs 1.80 s, same transcript).
Cold subprocess: TFLite-enc loses to whisper.cpp phone by 2.87x
                 (5.16 s vs 1.80 s) because Python starts from scratch.

The 2.5x encoder compute speedup from logs/pixel6_nnapi_accelerated_*.log
(505 ms TFLite vs 1262 ms ggml) is REAL and now reachable end-to-end,
but only if the runner stays alive across calls. Subprocess per
utterance pays the Python startup tax every time.

CORRECTNESS
-----------
Both paths produce the expected English transcript. TFLite path
actually retains more of the utterance ("stop" survives), probably
because the pytorch greedy decoder's EOT criterion is less aggressive
than ggml tiny's beam=5.

WHAT IS STILL BLOCKED
---------------------
End-to-end in the daemon as it stands TODAY: still blocked, because
demo/robot_daemon.py invokes scripts/whisper_tflite_runner.py via
subprocess.run per utterance. To capture the win:

  Option 1 (minimal): import whisper_tflite_runner in robot_daemon.py
    and call run_encoder_only() directly instead of shelling out. One
    import, ~10 lines changed. Pays the Python startup ONCE at daemon
    boot, then every subsequent utterance is ~1.25 s.

  Option 2 (more work): keep the runner as a separate long-lived
    process, talk to it over a UNIX socket. Useful if we want to
    isolate TF's import side-effects from the rest of the daemon.

Either option lands the 2.5x compute win as a ~30% wall-time win
(~0.55 s saved per voice turn). Recommended: Option 1. Task says
"don't touch demo/robot_daemon.py" so the wire change is left as a
follow-up.

